03809nam a22006015i 9780292792791DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212010txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927927917 a10.7560/7217772doi  a(DE-B1597)587866  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF395.J5bS76 2010eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a976.4/0049242221 aStone, Bryan Edward, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Chosen Folks :bJews on the Frontiers of Texas /cBryan Edward Stone. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue: Rope Walker, A True Story -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne: Los Judíos en la Frontera -- tTwo: A “Wild Indian Region”: At Home on the Frontier -- tThree: The Possum and the Zionist -- tFour: Texas News for Texas Jews -- tFive: Texas Jews and the Ku Klux Klan -- tSix: Traditional Judaism and the Beth Israel Revolt -- tSeven: Texas Jews Respond to the World Crises of the 1940s -- tEight: “Are You Going to Serve Us?”: Texas Jews and the Black Civil Rights Movement -- tNine: Interior Frontiers -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTexas has one of the largest Jewish populations in the South and West, comprising an often-overlooked vestige of the Diaspora. The Chosen Folks brings this rich aspect of the past to light, going beyond single biographies and photographic histories to explore the full evolution of the Jewish experience in Texas. Drawing on previously unpublished archival materials and synthesizing earlier research, Bryan Edward Stone begins with the crypto-Jews who fled the Spanish Inquisition in the late sixteenth century and then discusses the unique Texas-Jewish communities that flourished far from the acknowledged centers of Jewish history and culture. The effects of this peripheral identity are explored in depth, from the days when geographic distance created physical divides to the redefinitions of "frontier" that marked the twentieth century. The rise of the Ku Klux Klan, the creation of Israel in the wake of the Holocaust, and the civil rights movement are covered as well, raising provocative questions about the attributes that enabled Texas Jews to forge a distinctive identity on the national and world stage. Brimming with memorable narratives, The Chosen Folks brings to life a cast of vibrant pioneers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aJewszTexasxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292792791423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292792791/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK